<Project>
  <!-- Auto-imported by NuGet into PackageReference consumers of
       Verovio.NET (the file name matches the package id, and living under
       buildTransitive/ makes the import transitive).

       It delivers Verovio's font + glyph-bounding-box payload
       (verovio-data) into the consumer's build + publish output at
       runtimes/win-x64/native/verovio-data/, preserving the per-font
       subdirectory structure. Toolkit.Create() resolves that path on every
       platform via its cross-RID fallback
       (Toolkit.TryResolveVendoredResourcePath tries the current RID then
       win-x64), so one win-x64-located copy serves win-x64, win-arm64, and
       linux-x64 consumers alike.

       Why a targets-driven content copy instead of packing the data under
       runtimes/<rid>/native/ as a NuGet native runtime asset: native-asset
       delivery flattens nested directories and trips NETSDK1152 ("multiple
       publish output files with the same relative path", e.g.
       Bravura/0020.xml vs Gootville/0020.xml) on any `dotnet publish -r
       <rid>` — which is exactly how the reference consumer deploys. The
       <None>/Link/CopyToOutputDirectory items below preserve the structure
       and flow into both build output and publish output without the
       native-asset path collision. The native ENGINE binary
       (libverovio.dll / .so) IS a native asset — that's a single file per
       RID, so it has no collision. -->
  <ItemGroup Condition="Exists('$(MSBuildThisFileDirectory)verovio-data')">
    <None Include="$(MSBuildThisFileDirectory)verovio-data\**\*">
      <Link>runtimes\win-x64\native\verovio-data\%(RecursiveDir)%(Filename)%(Extension)</Link>
      <CopyToOutputDirectory>PreserveNewest</CopyToOutputDirectory>
      <Pack>false</Pack>
      <Visible>false</Visible>
    </None>
  </ItemGroup>
</Project>
